:::summary
Trigonometry is the branch of mathematics that studies the relationships between the angles and sides of triangles. Developed by ancient Greek and Islamic mathematicians, it is essential for navigation, physics, engineering, and all higher mathematics. The six trigonometric functions — sine, cosine, tangent, and their reciprocals — form the foundation of wave analysis, Fourier transforms, and the mathematical description of periodic phenomena.
:::

